'''Mitami Shrine''' (みたみじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Minami Ward (Sakai)|Q1041996|qid=Q1041996|lt=Minami Ward|1=Minami-ku, Sakai}}, {{ill|lt=Sakai|Q193428|qid=Q193428|1=Sakai}}, {{ill|lt=Osaka Prefecture|Q122723|qid=Q122723|1=Osaka Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and under the former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|qid=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} system it was a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}. The grove of {{ill|lt=Shiribukagashi|Q149476|qid=Q149476|1=Lithocarpus glaber}} in the precincts is selected as one of the {{ill|lt=100 Green Sites of Osaka|Q11439936|qid=Q11439936|1=Ōsaka Midori no Hyakusen}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* Principal deity - {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|Q2564508|qid=Q2564508|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|1=Ame-no-Koyane}}
* Jointly enshrined deities - {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|qid=Q272993|lt=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}}, {{ill|qid=Q10936701|lt=Ōmononushi|Q10936701|qid=Q10936701|1=Ōmononushi}}-no-Mikoto, {{ill|lt=Mikumari deity|Q11129547|qid=Q11129547|lt=Ame-no-Mikumari-no-Ōkami|1=Mikumari}}, {{ill|lt=Ichikishimahime|Q11059454|qid=Q11059454|qid=Q11059454|lt=Ichikishimahime-no-Mikoto|1=Ichikishima-hime}}, {{ill|lt=Emperor Ojin|Q317997|qid=Q317997|lt=Homuda-wake-no-Mikoto|1=Emperor Ōjin}}, {{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|qid=Q382005|1=Sugawara no Michizane}}, {{ill|lt=Izanagi|Q813858|qid=Q813858|lt=Izanagi-no-Ōkami|1=Izanagi}}, {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|qid=Q276944|1=Ōkuninushi}}-no-Mikoto

=== History ===
The exact founding date is unknown, but the name "Mitami Shrine" appears in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} completed in {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1327274|qid=Q1327274|lt=Engi|1=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|qid=Q30470|1=927}})<ref name="About Mitami">[https://www.mitami-shrine.com/about/ Mitami Shrine homepage: About Mitami Shrine]</ref>.

The origin of the shrine name is said to come from "Mitami no Atai" recorded in ''Shinsen Shōjiroku'' and the "Kamiwake entry of Izumi Province." It states that the Mitami no Atai clan were descendants of {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|Q2564508|qid=Q2564508|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|1=Ame-no-Koyane}}, and that the reading of "mitami" is corrected as "mitami" written 美多彌<ref name="About Mitami"/>.

In the era of {{ill|lt=Emperor Go-Daigo|Q313942|qid=Q313942|1=Emperor Go-Daigo}} during the {{ill|lt=Nanboku-chō period|Q264012|qid=Q264012|1=Nanboku-chō period}}, the shrine is said to have had an extensive precinct of 30,000 tsubo and magnificent buildings<ref name="About Mitami"/>. It was also revered as a guardian deity by {{ill|lt=Kusunoki Masashige|Q382234|qid=Q382234|1=Kusunoki Masashige}}.

In the 1500s, the shrine-temple Tokusen-ji ({{ill|lt=jingūji|Q1074971|qid=Q1074971|1=Jingū-ji}}) was built in the precincts, and shrine priests and temple clerics managed shrine affairs. It is also said to have been protected by {{ill|lt=Oda Nobunaga|Q171411|qid=Q171411|1=Oda Nobunaga}}, and thus adopted the Oda clan crest (five-leaf mokkō, {{ill|lt=mokkō crest|Q11519285|qid=Q11519285|1=Mokkō mon}}) as its shrine crest<ref name="Yuisyo">Mitami Shrine history text</ref>. However, in {{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|qid=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1577|Q6704|qid=Q6704|1=1577}}), it was burned in war during Nobunaga's attack on Saika in Kii ({{ill|lt=Kishū campaign|Q10855721|qid=Q10855721|1=Battle of Kishuu}}), together with nearby {{ill|lt=Hōkō-ji (Sakai)|Q65269233|qid=Q65269233|lt=Hōkō-ji|1=Hōkō-ji}}.

In {{ill|lt=Bunroku|Q1373039|qid=Q1373039|1=Bunroku}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1592|Q6769|qid=Q6769|1=1592}}), the honden was rebuilt by {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Wada Dōsan|1=UNKNOWN}} of the {{ill|lt=Kusunoki clan|Q11541208|qid=Q11541208|1=Kusunoki clan}}, and the shrine name was changed to Gozu Tennō-sha<ref name="About Yabusame">[https://www.mitami-shrine.com/yabusame/ Mitami Shrine homepage: About Yabusame]</ref>.

During the {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} separation of Shinto and Buddhism ({{ill|lt=shinbutsu bunri|Q1970535|qid=Q1970535|1=Shinbutsu bunri}}), Tokusen-ji was abolished and the shrine renamed Yasaka Shrine. It was ranked as a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}. In {{ill|lt=1907|Q2048|qid=Q2048|1=1907}} (Meiji 40), five nearby village shrines and three unranked shrines were merged, and it was renamed Mitami Shrine as listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}.

On March 29, {{ill|lt=2014|Q1999|qid=Q1999|1=2014}} ({{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|qid=Q234510|1=Heisei era}} 26), the {{ill|lt=yabusame|Q1886157|qid=Q1886157|1=Yabusame}} rite was revived<ref name="About Yabusame"/>.

The shrine grove covers 8,250 {{ill|lt=square meters|Q25343|qid=Q25343|lt=m<sup>2</sup>|1=Square metre}} and includes evergreen broadleaf trees such as {{ill|lt=Shiribukagashi|Q149476|qid=Q149476|1=Lithocarpus glaber}}, {{ill|lt=Arakashi|Q714124|qid=Q714124|1=Quercus glauca}}, {{ill|lt=sakaki|Q775470|qid=Q775470|1=Cleyera japonica}}, and camphor. Shiribukagashi in particular rarely forms a forest; because this grove lies near the eastern limit of its distribution, it was designated an Osaka Prefecture {{ill|lt=natural monument|Q23790|qid=Q23790|1=Natural monument}} in {{ill|lt=1973|Q2477|qid=Q2477|1=1973}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 48). The shiribukagashi grove is also selected as one of the {{ill|lt=100 Green Sites of Osaka|Q11439936|qid=Q11439936|1=Ōsaka Midori no Hyakusen}}<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url= http://www.pref.osaka.lg.jp/midorikikaku/toshiryokka/hyakusenn.html|title=100 Green Sites of Osaka|publisher=Osaka Prefecture |accessdate=2016-12-23}}</ref>.

=== Precincts ===
* Honden - rebuilt in the {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} period.
* Heiden - rebuilt in {{ill|lt=1972|Q2476|qid=Q2476|1=1972}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 47).
* Haiden - rebuilt in 1972 (Shōwa 47).
* Shrine office
* Bishūkan

